### ============================================================================
### service-policy — PER-APPLICATION CONFIGURATION walkthrough (ADR-029)
###   POST   /v1/apps/{app}/configuration    create   (201, ETag "1")
###   GET    /v1/apps/{app}/configuration    read     (200 + ETag)
###   PUT    /v1/apps/{app}/configuration    replace  (If-Match)
###   DELETE /v1/apps/{app}/configuration    remove   (If-Match, 204)
###
### Open in VS Code (REST Client) or IntelliJ HTTP Client; run top-down.
### Start the app first:  ./mvnw quarkus:dev    (Docker running for MongoDB + OIDC)
###
### WHAT THIS IS (ADR-029):
###   Per-application configuration is DATA, administered through this API — not
###   deployment configuration. Onboarding an application must not be a redeploy, and
###   one application's change must not restart the engine for all the others.
###   ADR-013's GLOBAL markers (which role means "admin") stay in application.properties;
###   what is per-application by nature lives here. The rule is that simple.
###
###   Two sections, each independently optional (but at least one must be present):
###     subjectAttributes — attribute name → claim path inside the token
###     pip               — where to fetch the attributes the token does NOT carry
###
### ⚠️ NOTHING CONSUMES THIS YET. The claim mapping and the PIP adapter are later ADRs.
###    Writing a configuration today changes no decision; /evaluate is untouched.
###    ADR-029 makes the document administrable and stops there.
###
### A SINGLETON, not a collection: one document per app, addressed by the path alone.
### There is no list endpoint — there is nothing to list within an application.
###
### Admin-gated (ADR-013) and nested under the app (ADR-026): `app` must NOT appear in
### any request body (sending it → 400 BAD_REQUEST, even if it matches the path).
### Writes are conditional: If-Match: "<revision>" (the ETag from a GET).
###   Missing/unparseable If-Match → 428 ; stale → 412.
### Errors are RFC 9457 application/problem+json (see docs/ERRORS.md).
### ============================================================================

@host = http://localhost:8080
@auth_admin = Bearer {{admin_jwt}}
@auth = Bearer {{jwt}}


### ============================================================================
### ABOUT credentialRef — READ THIS BEFORE CONFIGURING A PIP
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### `credentialRef` is a NAME, never a secret. It is the key under which the actual
### credential lives in the DEPLOYMENT's secret mechanism (properties, environment,
### secret store) — and it is a future adapter, not this code, that resolves it.
###
### This is deliberate (ADR-029 §secrets are referenced, never stored): a configuration
### collection that administrators can read must never become a place where credentials
### live. Putting a token or a password in this field does not "work insecurely" — it
### stores your secret in a readable admin document. Don't.
###
### The engine stores this string, echoes it back on GET, and does nothing else with it.
### ============================================================================


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1) CREATE the configuration of app "rh"  →  201 Created
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Note: NO "app" field in the body — the path carries it.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "subjectAttributes": {
    "rol": "resource_access.rh.roles",
    "area": "org.area"
  },
  "pip": {
    "url": "https://rh-backend/api/subjects/{sub}/attributes",
    "timeoutMs": 500,
    "cacheTtlSeconds": 300,
    "credentialRef": "rh-pip"
  }
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created, ETag: "1"
### { "app": "rh", "subjectAttributes": {…}, "pip": {…}, "revision": 1 }
### A BARE object — no envelope. Configuration is a single resource, so there is nothing
### to page or wrap. `app` IS returned (the server supplies it); it is only absent from
### request bodies.
###
### NOTE the {sub} in the url: it is REQUIRED. It is what makes the endpoint per-subject
### rather than one URL for everyone; the future adapter substitutes the subject id.
### NOTE also: the engine did NOT call that URL. See section 6.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2) GET it  →  200, read the ETag (needed to write)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK.  Headers: ETag: "1"


### 3) Only ONE section is fine — sections are independently optional
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/nami/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "subjectAttributes": { "rol": "realm_access.roles" }
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created — and the response OMITS "pip" entirely rather than returning
### an empty object. "Not configured" and "configured empty" are different answers, and
### only the first is representable (validation rejects the second).


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4) PUT — replace the FULL document (this is a replace, NOT a merge)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "1"

{
  "subjectAttributes": {
    "rol": "resource_access.rh.roles"
  }
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK, ETag: "2"
### ⚠️ The "pip" section from step 1 is GONE — it was omitted, so it was removed. A merge
### would leave "remove the attribute source" inexpressible without inventing a second
### verb. Send the whole document you want to end up with.


### 5) 428 PRECONDITION_REQUIRED — write without If-Match
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "subjectAttributes": { "rol": "realm_access.roles" } }

### EXPECTED  428  code: "PRECONDITION_REQUIRED"
### (An unparseable If-Match, e.g. If-Match: "abc", is refused the same way: never a
### blind write.)


### 6) 412 PRECONDITION_FAILED — stale If-Match
PUT {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "1"

{ "subjectAttributes": { "rol": "realm_access.roles" } }

### EXPECTED  412  code: "PRECONDITION_FAILED"  (extension: currentRevision: 2)
### The revision moved to 2 in step 4. Reload, re-apply, retry — the lost-update guard.
### Note: no `policyId` member; a configuration document has no policy id.
###
### The precondition is checked BEFORE the body is validated. Send a stale If-Match AND
### a malformed body and you get 412, not a validation report: a client reasoning about
### a document it has not seen needs "reload and look again" first.


### ============================================================================
### VALIDATION — syntax and bounds, checked on write (ADR-029)
### ============================================================================

### 7) 400 — a document that configures nothing
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "INVALID_APP_CONFIG"
### invalidParams: [{ "field": "configuration",
###                   "reason": "declare at least one of 'subjectAttributes' or 'pip'; …" }]
### An empty configuration is indistinguishable from having none, so it is refused
### rather than stored as a document that means nothing.


### 8) 400 — pip.url without the {sub} placeholder
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "pip": {
    "url": "https://kronia-backend/api/subjects/attributes",
    "timeoutMs": 500,
    "cacheTtlSeconds": 300,
    "credentialRef": "kronia-pip"
  }
}

### EXPECTED  400  → field "pip.url", reason "must contain the '{sub}' placeholder…"


### 9) 400 — wrong scheme (the placeholder is there, the scheme is not http/https)
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "pip": { "url": "ftp://kronia-backend/subjects/{sub}", "timeoutMs": 500,
           "cacheTtlSeconds": 300, "credentialRef": "kronia-pip" }
}

### EXPECTED  400  → field "pip.url", reason "must be an absolute http or https URL"


### 10) 400 — out-of-bounds timeout, and EVERY other violation in the same response
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "subjectAttributes": { "rol": "" },
  "pip": { "url": "ftp://backend/subjects", "timeoutMs": 99999,
           "cacheTtlSeconds": 999999, "credentialRef": "" }
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "INVALID_APP_CONFIG" with SIX invalidParams:
###   subjectAttributes.rol  → claim path must not be blank
###   pip.url                → must contain the '{sub}' placeholder…
###   pip.url                → must be an absolute http or https URL
###   pip.timeoutMs          → must be between 1 and 10000
###   pip.cacheTtlSeconds    → must be between 0 and 86400
###   pip.credentialRef      → must not be blank…
### One request, one response, the whole list. Dotted field paths so an operator can
### fix the document in one pass instead of one round-trip per mistake.


### 11) 400 — an empty "pip" section: all four fields are required once it is declared
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "pip": {} }

### EXPECTED  400 — four invalidParams, one per missing field. A partially configured
### source cannot be called at all, so "partially configured" is not a state.


### 12) THE SOURCE IS NEVER CONTACTED AT WRITE TIME
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "pip": { "url": "http://127.0.0.1:1/subjects/{sub}", "timeoutMs": 500,
           "cacheTtlSeconds": 300, "credentialRef": "kronia-pip" }
}

### EXPECTED  201 Created — INSTANTLY, even though nothing is listening on port 1.
### This is deliberate (ADR-029): a source that is down when configuration is written is
### not a configuration error, and an admin write that performs outbound calls is an
### admin write that can hang. Validation is syntax and bounds, nothing more.


### 13) 400 BAD_REQUEST — `app` in the body (ADR-026)
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/kronia/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "app": "kronia", "subjectAttributes": { "rol": "realm_access.roles" } }

### EXPECTED  400  →  "'app' must not be present in the body; it is determined by the path."
### Rejected for EXISTING, not for disagreeing.


### ============================================================================
### THE REST OF THE ERROR SURFACE
### ============================================================================

### 14) 409 APP_CONFIG_ALREADY_EXISTS — configuration is a singleton
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "subjectAttributes": { "rol": "realm_access.roles" } }

### EXPECTED  409  →  "App 'rh' already has a configuration; use PUT to replace it."
### Create is not an update: only PUT carries the If-Match guard.


### 15) 404 APP_CONFIG_NOT_FOUND — an app that was never configured
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/never-configured/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  404  code: "APP_CONFIG_NOT_FOUND"
### An ADMINISTRATIVE answer only. That app evaluates perfectly well — it just has no
### claim mapping and no attribute source, so subject attributes come only from the
### caller, exactly as the engine behaved before ADR-029.


### 16) 403 FORBIDDEN — non-admin token
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth}}

### EXPECTED  403  code: "FORBIDDEN"  (every configuration operation is admin-gated)


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 17) DELETE the configuration  →  204 No Content
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Use the current ETag ("2" after step 4) as If-Match.
DELETE {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
If-Match: "2"

### EXPECTED  204 No Content (empty body)
### UNGUARDED by design, unlike deleting an action catalogue entry. Nothing references a
### configuration document, and removing one cannot widen a decision: it withdraws the
### engine's ability to DERIVE attributes, which makes fewer things determinable and
### never more permitted. Under deny-overrides with defaultEffect DENY, fewer resolved
### attributes can only produce equal or stricter outcomes (ADR-011).


### 18) …and it is gone
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}

### EXPECTED  404  code: "APP_CONFIG_NOT_FOUND"


### ============================================================================
### CACHING AND STALENESS (ADR-029)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Configuration is cached in memory for its future readers, with a 60-second TTL, and
### ABSENCE is cached too — most applications have no configuration, and that is exactly
### the read that must not hit Mongo on every decision.
###
### Writes through this API invalidate the cache, so on the single-instance deployment
### this engine runs as today, a change is visible to the very next read. Should it ever
### run multi-instance, other instances converge within the TTL: 60 seconds is the
### documented staleness window, and the upper bound on how long a decision could be
### made against superseded configuration.
###
### Acceptable because configuration is additive capability, not permission: a stale copy
### resolves fewer or different attributes, which under deny-overrides can only be equal
### or stricter (ADR-011). No change stream, no polling.
### ============================================================================


### ============================================================================
### HOW TO OBTAIN TOKENS (dev)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### In quarkus:dev the OIDC dev services start a Keycloak. Get tokens via the Dev UI
### (http://localhost:8080/q/dev) → OIDC. {{admin_jwt}} must carry the admin marker
### (role "authz-admin" by default; configurable per ADR-013).
